snippet.textDisplay:
The mark of a good DM... not laughing at the silly stuff simply because, compared to the average gamer who does some really stupid crap in game, these guys are strictly amateur. But, again, this is a DM, and is, therefore, somewhat jaded to begin with. We develop a form of immunity after a while. In some cases, the only time a DM even smiles is when s/he comes across something in game that has some serious potential to screw the PCs over.

These dangerous DMs only laugh when the encounter has the potential of a possible TPK... or just to screw with his players just to watch them sweat a bit. It works even better when he tosses dice for some unknown reason and then remains silent with only a hint of a grin.

snippet.textDisplay: When I saw that it was Sam and Mercer, I knew what to expect. Sam was going to get anybody but Mercer to laugh, and Mercer was going to be a challenge for everyone. I wasn't surprised that Sam lost every round either, but I think he might have fared better if he had gone second. Mercer on the other hand has been dealing with the entire CR cast trying to trip him up for years, so he was going to be a tough nut to crack, and as for his skits, well he's known for his creativity and many voices, so I expected him to be amusing, but hit-and-miss with the humor. This played out almost exactly as I expected. I personally laughed more than I do at normal laugh challenges.
snippet.textOriginal: When I saw that it was Sam and Mercer, I knew what to expect. Sam was going to get anybody but Mercer to laugh, and Mercer was going to be a challenge for everyone.
